Commerzbank, Ingenico, Intesa, Siemens: Europe Equity Preview

-- B y   I n y o u n g   H w a n g
-- 
2011-05-22T22:01:25Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-05-22/commerzbank-ingenico-intesa-siemens-europe-equity-preview.html
Shares of the following companies may
have unusual moves in European trading. Stock symbols are in
parentheses.  The Stoxx Europe 600 Index fell 0.1 percent to 279.65. The
Stoxx 50 Index lost 0.1 percent to 2,618.18. The Euro Stoxx 50
Index, a benchmark for nations using the euro, declined 1.3
percent to 2,853.98.  Banif SGPS SA (BNF)  : The biggest bank in  Portugal ’s
island regions of Madeira and Azores reported first-quarter
consolidated net income of 6.3 million euros, according to a
regulatory filing. The shares fell 0.7 percent to 69 euro cents.  Commerzbank AG (CBK)  :  Germany ’s second-biggest bank
plans to raise about 5.3 billion euros ($7.5 billion) selling
new shares to help repay state aid. It will sell 2.44 billion
new shares at 2.18 euros apiece, the Frankfurt-based bank said
in a statement. Shareholders will be allowed to subscribe to 10
new shares for every 11 already held. The shares rose 0.7
percent to 3.95 euros.  IFG Group Plc (IFP)  : The company which bought U.K.
pension provider James Hay last year has received a second
takeover approach from its main shareholder, Fiordland
Investment Ltd., which has a 19 percent stake in the company,
the Sunday Times reported, without saying where it got the
information. The shares gained 2.9 percent to 1.75 euros.  Ingenico (ING)  SA: VeriFone Systems Inc., Hypercom Corp.
and the French maker of payment systems have abandoned plans for
Hypercom to divest its U.S. point-of-sale business to Ingenico,
the U.S. Justice Department said in a statement. The shares
declined 0.2 percent to 31.02 euros.  Intesa Sanpaolo SpA (ISP)  :  Italy ’s second-biggest bank
will start selling new shares at 1.369 euros each and offer 2
common shares for every 7 common savings shares held, in a 5
billion-euro offer aimed at strengthening its finances. Shares
fell 3.6 percent to 1.94 euros.  Mediaset SpA (MS)  : Sky Italia Srl, a rival of the
broadcaster controlled by Italian Prime Minister  Silvio
Berlusconi , said it didn’t renew a broadcasting contract with
Current TV for business reasons. The shares rose 0.7 percent to
4.16 euros.  National Grid Plc (NG/ LN): The operator of Britain’s
power-distribution network denied newspaper reports that it may
sell its U.S.-based Niagara Mohawk Power Corp. unit for more
than 1 billion pounds ($1.6 billion). The stock rose 1.6 percent
to 632.5 pence.  Siemens AG (SIE)  : The company has decided to abandon
nuclear power after the reactor accident in  Japan ’s Fukushima
plant damaged market potential, Handelsblatt said, citing
unidentified people close to the company. The shares fell 2.2
percent to 91.75 euros.  Vedanta Resources Plc (VED)  : The London-listed metals
miner plans to raise 4.5 billion pounds ($7.3 billion) by
selling shares in its Konkola Copper Mines unit, the Sunday
Times reported, without saying where it got the information. The
shares gained 0.7 percent to 2,126 pence.  To contact the reporter on this story:
